				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13127245/scp-5425#post-4720056</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Wed, 15 Jul 2020 10:14:35 +0000</pubDate>
								<wikidot:authorUserId>6522165</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>The anomaly itself is bogged down by verbosity to the point of confusion, at least for me. The terminal screens are similarly confusing, and I'm not sure of their context. It's almost like I don't know what's technobabble and what's relevant information. Oppenheimers logs are okay, if a little melodramatic and reaching. It's hard to appreciate the stand out bits when the article's concept is impenetrable.</p> <p>-1</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13127245#post-4696123</guid>
				<title>-1</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-13127245/scp-5425#post-4696123</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Mon, 22 Jun 2020 02:43:11 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Agent Lackman</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>5955572</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>This was&#8230; impossible to understand. The&#8230; computer logs? not really sure what they are&#8230; were entirely illegible, and Oppenheimer’s notes just barely easier to read. Also, the Trinity test was top secret, and was not televised. I have no idea of what the heat map was of, it’s clearly too cold to be from the trinity test, and actually shows something, so it isn’t of the black hole. This also just felt like a bunch of philosophical notes, not actually an scp article. And as far as OBELISK goes, what the hell is it?</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
